Cyber Threat Intelligence (CTI) Platforms

Threat intelligence, also known as cyber threat intelligence (CTI), is information gathered, processed, and analyzed to learn about a threat actor's motivations, targets, and attack patterns. In other words, the contextual information on threats and threat actors aids in mitigating and defending against these threats.

For example, the malware used in an attack is an excellent source of intel. Defenders can extract meaningful information to help stop the attack by analyzing the malware, such as the C2 IP address. C2 is the computer the attacker use to retain communications with compromised systems. Extracting this vital information allows defenders to create firewall rules that block all communications between compromised systems and the attacker.

Since threat intel involves dealing with a lot of information, the need arises for platforms to help defenders collect, store, and share information about specific threats such as IP address, URL, file hash, etc. These pieces of information are called "Indicators of Compromise" or simply IOC. Indicators of compromise will be discussed in-depth in the subsequent modules of this course.
 


The Malware Information Sharing Platform (MISP) is the most known threat intelligence platform. It is an open-source threat-sharing platform where analysts collaborate and share information about the latest threats and indicators of compromise. Christophe Vandeplas developed the project, and it is under a GPLv3 license.   

 

Figure - zoom in

Threat Intelligence technologies are not only used to store and share indicators of compromise (IOC). Other capabilities include:

  • Correlating information.
  • Getting intelligence from the Dark web.
  • Notifying teams, continuous monitoring of web content, and many others.


Another two projects that are worth checking are OpenCTI and YETI IOC Management Platform.

OpenCTI is an open-source platform allowing organizations to manage their cyber threat intelligence knowledge and observables. It has been created to structure, store, organize and visualize technical and non-technical information about cyber threats.

Figure - zoom in


Yeti is a platform for storing observables, signs of compromise, attackers' Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures (TTP), and threat information in a single, centralized location. Yeti can also enhance observables on your behalf (e.g., resolve domains, geolocate IPs) so you don't have to. It provides a web API to easily integrate with other tools in your SOC arsenal.
